subject: Re: Call of Cthulhu: adjust "This verbal jumble'Cthulhu' and 'R'lyeh'."
msgSnippet: Stress is such a fun thing. More and more I realize that having grown up out of an English-speaking area and gaining the majority of my vocabulary from written
messageBody:
Stress is such a fun thing. More and more I realize that having grown up out of an English-speaking area and gaining the majority of my vocabulary from written material makes my speech pattern a bit more... well, patterned than most other native speakers of the language.

--- In Read_Alphabet@yahoogroups.com, Vincent Reilly <vin.reilly@...> wrote:
>
> the dictionary tells me I'm wrong, but I say and QS it as s@b'tErin.
> Vin
>
> On 5/23/2013 11:59 PM, Nathan Sharfi wrote:
> >
> > From
> > <https://github.com/adiabatic/qs-literature/commit/5278e3608d778a89c8935567d9a743d0f9ec7f42>:
> >
> > - add [j] to "minuteness"
> > - s/v,/visitor,/
> > - s/ k / cult / (with .Utter for [V])
> > - "imagery" as [ImIdZrI]
> >
> > At this point I should probably mention that Lovecraft isn't for the
> > QS novice unless an Orthodox version is handy; [s@bt@rin] seemed like
> > "sub tureen" (unexpected, but I've been thrown bigger curve balls
> > before) until I flipped over to the Orthodox version and read
> > "subterrene".
> >
> >
>
